{"title_page": "Taiwan Allies International Protection and Enhancement Initiative Act", "text_new": "{{Short description|United States law strengthening US-Taiwan political and commercial relations}}\n{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n|shorttitle        = Taiwan Allies International Protection and Enhancement Initiative (TAIPEI) Act of 2019\n|othershorttitles  = \n|longtitle         = An Act to express United States support for Taiwan's diplomatic alliances around the world.\n|colloquialacronym = TAIPEI Act\n|nickname          = \n|enacted by        = 116th\n|effective date    = March 26, 2020\n|cite public law   = \n|cite statutes at large = \n|acts amended    = \n|acts repealed   = \n|title amended   = \n|sections created = \n|sections amended = \n|leghisturl      = https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/1678\n|introducedin    = Senate\n|introducedbill  = [https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/1678 S.1678]\n|introducedby    = [[Cory Gardner]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Colorado|CO]])\n|introduceddate  = May 23, 2019\n|committees      = [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|House Foreign Affairs]], [[House Ways and Means]], [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations]]\n|passedbody1     = Senate\n|passeddate1     = October 29, 2019\n|passedvote1     = unanimous consent\n|passedbody2     = House\n|passeddate2     = March 4, 2020\n|passedvote2     = [https://www.congress.gov/congressional-record/2020/03/04/house-section/article/H1494-4 415\u20130]\n|agreedbody3     = Senate\n|agreeddate3     = March 11, 2020\n|agreedvote3     = unanimous consent\n|signedpresident = [[Donald Trump]]\n|signeddate      = March 26, 2020\n|unsignedpresident = \n|unsigneddate    = \n|vetoedpresident = \n|vetoeddate      = \n|overriddenbody1 = \n|overriddendate1 = \n|overriddenvote1 = \n|overriddenbody2 = \n|overriddendate2 = \n|overriddenvote2 = \n|amendments      = \n|SCOTUS cases    = \n}}\n\nThe '''Taiwan Allies International Protection and Enhancement Initiative (TAIPEI) Act of 2019''' ('''TAIPEI Act'''; {{USStatute|116|135|134|278|2020|03|26}}; {{USBill|116|s|1678}}) is an [[Act of Congress|Act of the United States Congress]]. It aims to increase the scope of US relations with [[Taiwan]] and encourage other nations and international organizations to strengthen their official and unofficial ties with the island nation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hsu|first=Stacy|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202003270004|title=Trump signs TAIPEI Act into law|date=March 27, 2020|work=|access-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Central News Agency (Taiwan)|Central News Agency]]|last2=Huang|first2=Frances|last3=Chen|first3=Christie|last4=Lin|first4=Ko}}</ref>\n\nThe law is considered a further upgrade to [[Taiwan\u2013United States relations]]<ref>{{cite web | last1=Ben | first1=Blanchard | last2=Tian | first2=Yew Lun | title=U.S. increases support for Taiwan, China threatens to strike back | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-taiwan-usa/u-s-increases-support-for-taiwan-china-threatens-to-strike-back-idUSKBN21E0B7 | date=March 26, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> after passing the [[Taiwan Travel Act]] in 2018 and was passed at a time in which the [[People's Republic of China]] was engaged in a campaign to restrict the diplomatic space of Taiwan.\n\n==Background==\n{{See also|Cross-Strait relations}}\nAfter [[Tsai Ing-wen]] was inaugurated as [[President of the Republic of China|President of the Republic of China (Taiwan)]] in 2016, the PRC started an extensive campaign to isolate the island state internationally, and by 2019 the number of countries maintaining official relations with [[Taipei]] had fallen from 22 to 15.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|date=20 September 2019|title=As Taiwan Loses Influence, China Gains Ground in Race With U.S.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/world/asia/taiwan-kiribati-china.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, following the election of [[Donald Trump]] as [[President of the United States|U.S. president]], [[China\u2013United States relations|U.S.\u2013China relations]] had deteriorated, especially since the start of the [[China\u2013United States trade war]] in 2018. While Taiwan felt its international space shrinking, relations with the US saw major breakthroughs, including a [[Trump\u2013Tsai call|phone call between Trump and Tsai]], the passage of the [[Taiwan Travel Act]], and cabinet-level meetings between the two countries. In order to disincentivize remaining countries to switch recognition away from Taiwan, and to allow the island greater participation in international organizations, the TAIPEI Act was conceived.\n\n==Provisions==\nProvisions of the TAIPEI Act state that the U.S. should:<ref name=\"senate\">{{cite web|date=23 May 2019|title=S.1678 - Taiwan Allies International Protection and Enhancement Initiative (TAIPEI) Act of 2019|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/1678/actions?KWICView=false|work=United States Congress|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Advocate, as appropriate, for Taiwan\u2019s membership in all international organizations in which statehood is not a requirement and in which the United States is also a participant; and for Taiwan to be granted observer status in other appropriate international organizations;\n*To instruct, as appropriate, representatives of the United States Government in all organizations to use the voice, vote, and influence of the United States to advocate for Taiwan\u2019s membership or observer status in such organizations;\n*To advocate, as appropriate, for Taiwan\u2019s membership or observer status in all organizations as part of any relevant bilateral engagements between the United States and the People\u2019s Republic of China, including leader summits and the U.S.-China Comprehensive Economic Dialogue.\n\n==Reaction==\n===Taiwan===\nAfter the U.S. House of Representatives unanimously passed the act, Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen expressed thanks and said that \"her country will continue to work with the U.S. to contribute to the peaceful and stable development of the Indo-Pacific Region.\"<ref name=\"taiwan news\">{{cite news|date=5 March 2020|title=Taiwan president thanks US House for passing Taipei Act|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3890601|work=[[Taiwan News]]|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===People's Republic of China===\nChina opposed the passing of the act, calling the move a severe violation of the [[One-China policy|one-China principle]] and the three China-U.S. joint communiques. It reiterated its stance that China has long been opposed to any form of official exchanges between Taiwan and the United States.\"<ref name=\"CGTN\">{{cite news|date=5 March 2020|title=China firmly opposes U.S. TAIPEI Act, urges proper handling of issue|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-03-05/China-firmly-opposes-U-S-TAIPEI-Act-urges-proper-handling-of-issue-OC3kf063ao/index.html|work=[[CGTN]]|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=China denounces new U.S. law on supporting Taiwan | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-taiwan-usa-china/china-denounces-new-u-s-law-on-supporting-taiwan-idUSKBN21E0X4 | date=March 27, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n[[Speaker of the House]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] underlined the bipartisan support that helped pass the act and stated that it \"celebrates and supports Taiwan\u2019s commitment to democracy, by preserving and promoting its position on the international stage.\"<ref name=\"Speaker of the House\">{{cite news|date=4 March 2020|title=Pelosi Statement on Passage of TAIPEI Act|url=https://www.speaker.gov/newsroom/3420-1|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Taiwan Relations Act]]\n*[[Taiwan Travel Act]]\n*[[Six Assurances]]\n*[[Political status of Taiwan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BC_CBp9Dhl4 TAIPEI Act on House Floor]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0aEYkgX8ZW8 President Tsai thanks US House of Representatives for passing TAIPEI Act]\n\n{{Foreign relations of the United States}}\n{{Foreign relations of Taiwan}}\n\n[[Category:Acts of the 116th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:2020 in American law]]\n[[Category:Taiwan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:2020 in international relations]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1991\u2013present)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|United States law strengthening US-Taiwan political and commercial relations}}\n{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n|shorttitle        = Taiwan Allies International Protection and Enhancement Initiative (TAIPEI) Act of 2019\n|othershorttitles  = \n|longtitle         = An Act to express United States support for Taiwan's diplomatic alliances around the world.\n|colloquialacronym = TAIPEI Act\n|nickname          = \n|enacted by        = 116th\n|effective date    = March 26, 2020\n|cite public law   = \n|cite statutes at large = \n|acts amended    = \n|acts repealed   = \n|title amended   = \n|sections created = \n|sections amended = \n|leghisturl      = https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/1678\n|introducedin    = Senate\n|introducedbill  = [https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/1678 S.1678]\n|introducedby    = [[Cory Gardner]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Colorado|CO]])\n|introduceddate  = May 23, 2019\n|committees      = [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|House Foreign Affairs]], [[House Ways and Means]], [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations]]\n|passedbody1     = Senate\n|passeddate1     = October 29, 2019\n|passedvote1     = unanimous consent\n|passedbody2     = House\n|passeddate2     = March 4, 2020\n|passedvote2     = [https://www.congress.gov/congressional-record/2020/03/04/house-section/article/H1494-4 415\u20130]\n|agreedbody3     = Senate\n|agreeddate3     = March 11, 2020\n|agreedvote3     = unanimous consent\n|signedpresident = [[Donald Trump]]\n|signeddate      = March 26, 2020\n|unsignedpresident = \n|unsigneddate    = \n|vetoedpresident = \n|vetoeddate      = \n|overriddenbody1 = \n|overriddendate1 = \n|overriddenvote1 = \n|overriddenbody2 = \n|overriddendate2 = \n|overriddenvote2 = \n|amendments      = \n|SCOTUS cases    = \n}}\n\nThe '''Taiwan Allies International Protection and Enhancement Initiative (TAIPEI) Act of 2019''' ('''TAIPEI Act'''; {{USStatute|116|135|134|278|2020|03|26}}; {{USBill|116|s|1678}}) is an [[Act of Congress|Act of the United States Congress]]. It aims to increase the scope of US relations with [[Taiwan]] and encourage other nations and international organizations to strengthen their official and unofficial ties with the island nation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hsu|first=Stacy|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202003270004|title=Trump signs TAIPEI Act into law|date=March 27, 2020|work=|access-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Central News Agency (Taiwan)|Central News Agency]]|last2=Huang|first2=Frances|last3=Chen|first3=Christie|last4=Lin|first4=Ko}}</ref>\n\nThe law is considered a further upgrade to [[Taiwan\u2013United States relations]]<ref>{{cite web | last1=Ben | first1=Blanchard | last2=Tian | first2=Yew Lun | title=U.S. increases support for Taiwan, China threatens to strike back | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-taiwan-usa/u-s-increases-support-for-taiwan-china-threatens-to-strike-back-idUSKBN21E0B7 | date=March 26, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> after passing the [[Taiwan Travel Act]] in 2018 and was passed at a time in which the [[People's Republic of China]] was engaged in a campaign to restrict the diplomatic space of Taiwan.\n\n==Background==\n{{See also|Cross-Strait relations}}\nAfter [[Tsai Ing-wen]] was inaugurated as [[President of the Republic of China|President of the Republic of China (Taiwan)]] in 2016, the PRC started an extensive campaign to isolate the island state internationally, and by 2019 the number of countries maintaining official relations with [[Taipei]] had fallen from 22 to 15.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|date=20 September 2019|title=As Taiwan Loses Influence, China Gains Ground in Race With U.S.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/world/asia/taiwan-kiribati-china.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, following the election of [[Donald Trump]] as [[President of the United States|U.S. president]], [[China\u2013United States relations|U.S.\u2013China relations]] had deteriorated, especially since the start of the [[China\u2013United States trade war]] in 2018. While Taiwan felt its international space shrinking, relations with the US saw major breakthroughs, including a [[Trump\u2013Tsai call|phone call between Trump and Tsai]], the passage of the [[Taiwan Travel Act]], and cabinet-level meetings between the two countries. In order to disincentivize remaining countries to switch recognition away from Taiwan, and to allow the island greater participation in international organizations, the TAIPEI Act was conceived.\n\n==Provisions==\nProvisions of the TAIPEI Act state that the U.S. should:<ref name=\"senate\">{{cite web|date=23 May 2019|title=S.1678 - Taiwan Allies International Protection and Enhancement Initiative (TAIPEI) Act of 2019|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/1678/actions?KWICView=false|work=United States Congress|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Advocate, as appropriate, for Taiwan\u2019s membership in all international organizations in which statehood is not a requirement and in which the United States is also a participant; and for Taiwan to be granted observer status in other appropriate international organizations;\n*To instruct, as appropriate, representatives of the United States Government in all organizations to use the voice, vote, and influence of the United States to advocate for Taiwan\u2019s membership or observer status in such organizations;\n*To advocate, as appropriate, for Taiwan\u2019s membership or observer status in all organizations as part of any relevant bilateral engagements between the United States and the People\u2019s Republic of China, including leader summits and the U.S.-China Comprehensive Economic Dialogue.\n\n==Reaction==\n===Taiwan===\nAfter the U.S. House of Representatives unanimously passed the act, Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen expressed thanks and said that \"her country will continue to work with the U.S. to contribute to the peaceful and stable development of the Indo-Pacific Region.\"<ref name=\"taiwan news\">{{cite news|date=5 March 2020|title=Taiwan president thanks US House for passing Taipei Act|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3890601|work=[[Taiwan News]]|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===People's Republic of China===\nChina opposed the passing of the act, calling the move a severe violation of the [[One-China policy|one-China principle]] and the three China-U.S. joint communiques. It reiterated its stance that China has long been opposed to any form of official exchanges between Taiwan and the United States.\"<ref name=\"CGTN\">{{cite news|date=5 March 2020|title=China firmly opposes U.S. TAIPEI Act, urges proper handling of issue|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-03-05/China-firmly-opposes-U-S-TAIPEI-Act-urges-proper-handling-of-issue-OC3kf063ao/index.html|work=[[CGTN]]|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=China denounces new U.S. law on supporting Taiwan | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-taiwan-usa-china/china-denounces-new-u-s-law-on-supporting-taiwan-idUSKBN21E0X4 | date=March 27, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n[[Speaker of the House]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] underlined the bipartisan support that helped pass the act and stated that it \"celebrates and supports Taiwan\u2019s commitment to democracy, by preserving and promoting its position on the international stage.\"<ref name=\"Speaker of the House\">{{cite news|date=4 March 2020|title=Pelosi Statement on Passage of TAIPEI Act|url=https://www.speaker.gov/newsroom/3420-1|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Taiwan Relations Act]]\n*[[Six Assurances]]\n*[[Political status of Taiwan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BC_CBp9Dhl4 TAIPEI Act on House Floor]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0aEYkgX8ZW8 President Tsai thanks US House of Representatives for passing TAIPEI Act]\n\n{{Foreign relations of the United States}}\n{{Foreign relations of Taiwan}}\n\n[[Category:Acts of the 116th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:2020 in American law]]\n[[Category:Taiwan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:2020 in international relations]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1991\u2013present)]]\n", "name_user": "Bokmanrocks01", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taiwan_Allies_International_Protection_and_Enhancement_Initiative_Act"}
{"title_page": "Jeremiah Riggs", "text_new": "{{short description|American mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Jeremiah Riggs\n| other_names     = Bigg Rigg <br>Mississippi\n| image           = JRiggs.jpg\n| image_size      = 200px\n| alt             =\n| caption         =\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1982|12|17}}\n| birth_place     = [[Vicksburg, Mississippi]], United States\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| residence       =\n| nationality     =  [[People of the United States|American]]\n| height          = {{height|ft=6|in=0}}\n| weight          = {{convert|180|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n| weight_class    = [[Middleweight (MMA)|Middleweight]]<br>[[Welterweight (MMA)|Welterweight]]\n| reach           = \n| style           = \n| stance          = \n| fighting_out_of = [[Springfield, Illinois]]\n| team            = Fiore MMA\n| rank            =\n| years_active    = 2007-present\n| mma_kowin       = 1\n| mma_subwin      = 3\n| mma_decwin      = 3\n| mma_koloss      = 1\n| mma_subloss     = 5\n| mma_decloss     = 2\n| mma_draw        = \n| mma_nc          = \n| url             =\n| sherdog         = 24469\n| footnotes       =\n| updated         =\n}}\n\n'''Jeremiah Riggs''' (born December 12, 1982) is an [[United States|American]] [[professional wrestler]], and [[mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] who competes in the [[Welterweight (MMA)|welterweight]] and [[Middleweight (MMA)|middleweight]] divisions. A professional MMA competitor since 2007, Riggs has made a name for himself mainly fighting in the Midwest, and his home state of [[Mississippi]]. He was a competitor on [[SpikeTV]]'s ''[[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Rampage vs Team Forrest]]'' as well as a contestant on ''[[WWE Tough Enough]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nRiggs was born and raised in [[Vicksburg, Mississippi]]. He is the son of an E-9 who served four years in the Coast Guard followed by 31 years in the National Guard.<ref name=\"Bio1\">{{cite web|url=http://rhinoden.rangerup.com/meet-jeremiah-riggs/ |title=Meet Jeremiah Riggs - &#124; @TheRhinoDen &#124; Home Of All Things Military |website=Rhinoden.rangerup.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref> Riggs attended his local high school, playing baseball and football, lettering in both sports. After graduating high school Riggs went on to enroll into [[Mississippi Delta Community College]] where he was on the football team.<ref name=\"Bio2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usanetwork.com/series/toughenough/theshow/characterprofiles/riggs/ |title=WWE Tough Enough &#124; Reality Series |publisher=USA Network |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\nUpon graduating from college Riggs signed up with the [[United States Army]] and served a tour in [[Afghanistan]] with the 1st Ranger Battalion.<ref name=\"Bio1\" /> After leaving the Army in 2005, Riggs worked around Mississippi driving trucks for a living; even owning his own trucking business.\n\n==Mixed martial arts==\nRiggs made his professional debut against Craig Sjoerdsma in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]]. Riggs won the fight via submission from strikes in the first round. Riggs then fought Robert Thompson for the Southern Fighting Alliance middleweight title belt. The fight lasted all 5 rounds, and Riggs narrowly lost a decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=frpWVL3t2QM |title=Jeremiah Riggs Alabama Pride Video Blog Episode 4 |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-11-30 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref> During the fight, one of Riggs' front teeth was knocked out. In 2007 Riggs sold his trucking company and moved to San Jose to train MMA with [[Frank Shamrock]]. Riggs was set to become part of the [[San Jose Razorclaws]], an [[International Fight League]] team coached by Shamrock, but the team was disbanded by the IFL before the season began.<ref name=\"Bio1\" />\n\nAfter the IFL dissolved Riggs was invited to be a part of season seven of ''[[The Ultimate Fighter]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/3624/jeremiah-riggs-picked-for-the-ultimate-fighter-7-cast.mma |title=Jeremiah Riggs Picked for \"The Ultimate Fighter 7\" Cast |last=Stupp |first=Dann |date=January 28, 2008 |website=MMAjunkie.com |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026112427/http://mmajunkie.com/news/3624/jeremiah-riggs-picked-for-the-ultimate-fighter-7-cast.mma |archivedate=October 26, 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref> Riggs was paired against [[Dan Cramer]] in a preliminary match-up to see who obtained entry into the house.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ultimatefighter.com/fight-videos/2419/tuf-7-dan-cramer-jeremiah-riggs |title=Dan Cramer vs. Jeremiah Riggs - ROUND 2 |author= |date= |website=UltimateFighter.com |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222205056/http://www.ultimatefighter.com/fight-videos/2419/tuf-7-dan-cramer-jeremiah-riggs |archivedate=December 22, 2011 |accessdate=}}</ref> Riggs lost a decision, but earned the respect of UFC President [[Dana White]] and [[Quinton Jackson]]. After filming on TUF Riggs moved to [[Granite City, Illinois]] to train with [[Matt Hughes (fighter)|Matt Hughes]] at The HIT Squad.\n\nRiggs took a fight against up-and-comer [[Dom O'Grady]], losing the fight via submission late in the last round of the fight. The loss was the start of a four-fight losing streak stretching from 2008 to 2010. During that time he saw defeat from soon-to-be teammate Ken Jackson, and future UFC fighter [[John Salter]]. Riggs broke the streak in February 2010 after pulling off an impressive triangle choke submission over Jesse Beale. After suffering his last loss Riggs went on a five fight winning streak; with wins coming inside the [[Bellator Fighting Championships]], and [[Strikeforce (mixed martial arts)|Strikeforce]].<ref name=\"Bio2\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bellator.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=23600&ATCLID=204995702 |title=Bellator 30 - Fourth Street Live, Louisville, KY |author= |date= |website=Bellator.com |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515222042/http://www.bellator.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=23600&ATCLID=204995702 |archivedate=May 15, 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aroundtheoctagon.com/?p=8542 |title=Jeremiah Riggs talks about win at \"Middle Tennessee Mayhem\" and what could be next |author= |date=February 1, 2011 |website=AroundTheOctagon.com |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005232830/http://www.aroundtheoctagon.com/?p=8542 |archivedate=October 5, 2011 |accessdate=}}</ref> In 2011, Riggs officially retired from MMA to pursue a career in professional wrestling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prommanow.com/index.php/2011/04/06/tough-enough-contestant-jeremiah-riggs-talks-about-making-the-transition-from-mma-to-pro-wrestling-exclusive/ |title=Tough Enough contestant Jeremiah Riggs on transition from MMA to pro wrestling \u2013 exclusive |publisher=Pro MMA Now |date=2011-04-06 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2012 Riggs officially came out of retirement at [[Bellator Fighting Championships: Season Six#Bellator LXI|Bellator 61]] in [[Bossier City, Louisiana]] to fight Trey Houston in a \"Middleweight Tournament Qualifier\". In 2015 Riggs walked away from MMA and pursued a career in bull riding, competing on small circuits in the midwest and southeast United States.\n\n==Television career==\nAfter competing on [[The Ultimate Fighter]] Riggs was selected to go on VH1's hit reality show ''[[Daisy of Love]]''. In an MMA fight arranged by the show's producers, Riggs defeated VH1 reality personality \"12 Pack\" which saw 12 Pack suffer a broken nose and sent to the hospital. Riggs finished fifth on the show.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120618181801/http://squareeyes.blinkx.com/tag/big-rig/ http://squareeyes.blinkx.com/tag/big-rig/ ]</ref>\n\nWhen filming of ''Daisy of Love'' ended, Riggs was selected to be a part of another VH1 series ''[[I Love Money 3]]''. The show was never aired due to another contestant who killed his own wife before committing suicide.<ref name=\"Bio1\" />\n\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name=Jeremiah Riggs\n|names='''Jeremiah Riggs''',<br>Big Rigg,<br>Mississippi\n|image=\n|caption=\n|height={{height|feet=6|inch=0}}\n|weight={{convert|200|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1982|12|17}}\n|birth_place=[[Vicksburg, Mississippi]]\n|resides=[[Granite City, Illinois]],<br>[[Vicksburg, Mississippi]]\n|trainer= [[Matt Hughes (fighter)|Matt Hughes]],<br>[[Dutch Mantel]],<br>[[Bill DeMott]]\n}}\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\nRiggs began his professional wrestling career training with [[Dutch Mantel]] in [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Clendaniel |first=Brett |url=http://wrestlechat.net/dutch-mantel-endorses-a-wwe-tough-enough-candidate/ |title=Dutch Mantel Endorses a WWE Tough Enough Candidate |website=Wrestlechat.net |date=2015-12-18 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\n===WWE===\n\n====Tough Enough====\nIn March 2011, he was announced as one of the fourteen contestants for the return of ''[[WWE Tough Enough]]'' on the USA Network.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/22850/tuf-7-vet-jeremiah-riggs-set-for-wwes-tough-enough-series.mma |title=\"TUF 7\" vet Jeremiah Riggs set for WWE's \"Tough Enough\" series |author= |date=March 16, 2011 |website=MMAjunkie.com |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109160435/http://mmajunkie.com/news/22850/tuf-7-vet-jeremiah-riggs-set-for-wwes-tough-enough-series.mma |archivedate=November 9, 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref> Throughout the show, Riggs was complimented on his heart and athleticism. He was nicknamed \"MMA\" by the trainers because of his mixed martial arts background. Along with Martin, he was one of just two contestants to not get stuck in the bottom three. Riggs finished third on the show, being eliminated in week nine because of his inexperience inside the ring.\n\n====Florida Championship Wrestling (2011)====\nIn May 2011, Riggs made his debut for [[Florida Championship Wrestling]], the developmental territory for the WWE. He defeated [[Peter Orlov]] in his first match as a part of the ''Tough Enough'' finale.<ref name=\"FCWTE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/58150/detailed-spoilers-from-tough-enough-segments-taped-at-fcw-television-tapings.html?p=1|title=DETAILED SPOILERS FROM TOUGH ENOUGH SEGMENTS TAPED AT FCW TELEVISION TAPINGS|publisher=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> However, Riggs was released after being informed that WWE had no interest in signing him following the tryout in FCW after rubbing officials and other wrestlers the wrong way.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.aroundtheoctagon.com/jeremiah-riggs-blasts-fcw/ |title=Jeremiah Riggs blasts FCW |website=AroundTheOctagon.com |date=2011-08-02 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[The Ultimate Fighter]]'' || Himself || [[TV Series]]\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Daisy of Love]]'' || Himself || [[TV Series]]\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[WWE Tough Enough]]'' || Himself || [[TV Series]]\n|-\n| 2015 || [[Steve Austin's Broken Skull Challenge]] || Himself || [[TV Series]]\n|}\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n| draws= \n| nc= \n| ko-wins= 3\n| ko-losses= 1\n| sub-wins= 1\n| sub-losses= 5\n| dec-wins= 3\n| dec-losses= 2\n| dq-wins= \n| dq-losses= \n| other-wins= \n| other-losses= \n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 7\u20138\n| Peter Aspenwal\n| Decision (split)\n| [[Bellator 101]]\n| {{dts|2013|September|27}}\n| align=center| 3\n| align=center| 5:00\n| [[Portland, Oregon]], United States\n|\n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 7\u20137\n| [[Kelvin Tiller]]\n| Submission (Kimura)\n| [[Bellator Fighting Championships: Season Six#Bellator LXX|Bellator 70]]\n| {{dts|2012|May|25}}\n| align=center| 3\n| align=center| 3:38\n| [[New Orleans, Louisiana]], United States\n|\n|-\n| {{no2}