| 1\u20134\n| Eric Irvin\n| Decision (unanimous)\n| Devastation Fight Club\n| {{dts|2010|January|30}}\n| align=center| 3\n| align=center| 3:00\n| [[Cape Girardeau, Missouri]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{No2}}Loss\n| align=center| 1\u20133\n| [[John Salter]]\n| TKO (punches)\n| CCCW: The 3rd Degree\n| {{dts|2009|October|17}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 4:44\n| [[Springfield, Illinois]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{No2}}Loss\n| align=center| 1\u20132\n| Ken Jackson\n| Submission (rear-naked choke)\n| Arkansas MMA: Ultimate Fight Night 6\n| {{dts|2009|November|28}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 3:07\n| [[Fort Smith, Arkansas]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{No2}}Loss\n| align=center| 1\u20131\n| [[Dom O'Grady]]\n| Submission (guillotine choke)\n| XFO 25: Outdoor War 4\n| {{dts|2008|August|09}}\n| align=center| 3\n| align=center| 4:16\n| [[Island Lake, Illinois]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{Yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 1\u20130\n| Craig Sjoerdsma\n| TKO (submission to punches)\n| Ultimate Cage Fighting: Rage in the Cage\n| {{dts|2007|September|22}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| N/A\n| [[New Orleans]], United States\n| \n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Sherdog}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riggs, Jeremiah}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American male mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Middleweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Tough Enough contestants]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Vicksburg, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:United States Army personnel]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Jeremiah Riggs\n| other_names     = Bigg Rigg <br>Mississippi\n| image           = JRiggs.jpg\n| image_size      = 200px\n| alt             =\n| caption         =\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1982|12|17}}\n| birth_place     = [[Vicksburg, Mississippi]], United States\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| residence       =\n| nationality     =  [[People of the United States|American]]\n| height          = {{height|ft=6|in=0}}\n| weight          = {{convert|180|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n| weight_class    = [[Middleweight (MMA)|Middleweight]]<br>[[Welterweight (MMA)|Welterweight]]\n| reach           = \n| style           = \n| stance          = \n| fighting_out_of = [[Springfield, Illinois]]\n| team            = Fiore MMA\n| rank            =\n| years_active    = 2007-present\n| mma_kowin       = 1\n| mma_subwin      = 3\n| mma_decwin      = 3\n| mma_koloss      = 1\n| mma_subloss     = 5\n| mma_decloss     = 2\n| mma_draw        = \n| mma_nc          = \n| url             =\n| sherdog         = 24469\n| footnotes       =\n| updated         =\n}}\n\n'''Jeremiah Riggs''' (born December 12, 1982) is an [[United States|American]] [[professional wrestler]], and [[mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] who competes in the [[Welterweight (MMA)|welterweight]] and [[Middleweight (MMA)|middleweight]] divisions. A professional MMA competitor since 2007, Riggs has made a name for himself mainly fighting in the Midwest, and his homestate of [[Mississippi]]. He was a competitor on [[SpikeTV]]'s ''[[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Rampage vs Team Forrest]]'' as well as a contestant on ''[[WWE Tough Enough]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nRiggs was born and raised in [[Vicksburg, Mississippi]]. He is the son of an E-9 who served four years in the Coast Guard followed by 31 years in the National Guard.<ref name=\"Bio1\">{{cite web|url=http://rhinoden.rangerup.com/meet-jeremiah-riggs/ |title=Meet Jeremiah Riggs - &#124; @TheRhinoDen &#124; Home Of All Things Military |website=Rhinoden.rangerup.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref> Riggs attended his local high school, playing baseball and football, lettering in both sports. After graduating high school Riggs went on to enroll into [[Mississippi Delta Community College]] where he was on the football team.<ref name=\"Bio2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usanetwork.com/series/toughenough/theshow/characterprofiles/riggs/ |title=WWE Tough Enough &#124; Reality Series |publisher=USA Network |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\nUpon graduating from college Riggs signed up with the [[United States Army]] and served a tour in [[Afghanistan]] with the 1st Ranger Battalion.<ref name=\"Bio1\" /> After leaving the Army in 2005, Riggs worked around Mississippi driving trucks for a living; even owning his own trucking business.\n\n==Mixed martial arts==\nRiggs made his professional debut against Craig Sjoerdsma in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]]. Riggs won the fight via submission from strikes in the first round. Riggs then fought Robert Thompson for the Southern Fighting Alliance middleweight title belt. The fight lasted all 5 rounds, and Riggs narrowly lost a decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=frpWVL3t2QM |title=Jeremiah Riggs Alabama Pride Video Blog Episode 4 |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-11-30 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref> During the fight, one of Riggs' front teeth was knocked out. In 2007 Riggs sold his trucking company and moved to San Jose to train MMA with [[Frank Shamrock]]. Riggs was set to become part of the [[San Jose Razorclaws]], an [[International Fight League]] team coached by Shamrock, but the team was disbanded by the IFL before the season began.<ref name=\"Bio1\" />\n\nAfter the IFL dissolved Riggs was invited to be a part of season seven of ''[[The Ultimate Fighter]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/3624/jeremiah-riggs-picked-for-the-ultimate-fighter-7-cast.mma |title=Jeremiah Riggs Picked for \"The Ultimate Fighter 7\" Cast |last=Stupp |first=Dann |date=January 28, 2008 |website=MMAjunkie.com |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026112427/http://mmajunkie.com/news/3624/jeremiah-riggs-picked-for-the-ultimate-fighter-7-cast.mma |archivedate=October 26, 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref> Riggs was paired against [[Dan Cramer]] in a preliminary match-up to see who obtained entry into the house.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ultimatefighter.com/fight-videos/2419/tuf-7-dan-cramer-jeremiah-riggs |title=Dan Cramer vs. Jeremiah Riggs - ROUND 2 |author= |date= |website=UltimateFighter.com |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222205056/http://www.ultimatefighter.com/fight-videos/2419/tuf-7-dan-cramer-jeremiah-riggs |archivedate=December 22, 2011 |accessdate=}}</ref> Riggs lost a decision, but earned the respect of UFC President [[Dana White]] and [[Quinton Jackson]]. After filming on TUF Riggs moved to [[Granite City, Illinois]] to train with [[Matt Hughes (fighter)|Matt Hughes]] at The HIT Squad.\n\nRiggs took a fight against up-and-comer [[Dom O'Grady]], losing the fight via submission late in the last round of the fight. The loss was the start of a four-fight losing streak stretching from 2008 to 2010. During that time he saw defeat from soon-to-be teammate Ken Jackson, and future UFC fighter [[John Salter]]. Riggs broke the streak in February 2010 after pulling off an impressive triangle choke submission over Jesse Beale. After suffering his last loss Riggs went on a five fight winning streak; with wins coming inside the [[Bellator Fighting Championships]], and [[Strikeforce (mixed martial arts)|Strikeforce]].<ref name=\"Bio2\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bellator.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=23600&ATCLID=204995702 |title=Bellator 30 - Fourth Street Live, Louisville, KY |author= |date= |website=Bellator.com |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515222042/http://www.bellator.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=23600&ATCLID=204995702 |archivedate=May 15, 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aroundtheoctagon.com/?p=8542 |title=Jeremiah Riggs talks about win at \"Middle Tennessee Mayhem\" and what could be next |author= |date=February 1, 2011 |website=AroundTheOctagon.com |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005232830/http://www.aroundtheoctagon.com/?p=8542 |archivedate=October 5, 2011 |accessdate=}}</ref> In 2011, Riggs officially retired from MMA to pursue a career in professional wrestling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prommanow.com/index.php/2011/04/06/tough-enough-contestant-jeremiah-riggs-talks-about-making-the-transition-from-mma-to-pro-wrestling-exclusive/ |title=Tough Enough contestant Jeremiah Riggs on transition from MMA to pro wrestling \u2013 exclusive |publisher=Pro MMA Now |date=2011-04-06 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2012 Riggs officially came out of retirement at [[Bellator Fighting Championships: Season Six#Bellator LXI|Bellator 61]] in [[Bossier City, Louisiana]] to fight Trey Houston in a \"Middleweight Tournament Qualifier\". In 2015 Riggs walked away from MMA and pursued a career in bull riding, competing on small circuits in the midwest and southeast United States.\n\n==Television career==\nAfter competing on [[The Ultimate Fighter]] Riggs was selected to go on VH1's hit reality show ''[[Daisy of Love]]''. In an MMA fight arranged by the show's producers, Riggs defeated VH1 reality personality \"12 Pack\" which saw 12 Pack suffer a broken nose and sent to the hospital. Riggs finished fifth on the show.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120618181801/http://squareeyes.blinkx.com/tag/big-rig/ http://squareeyes.blinkx.com/tag/big-rig/ ]</ref>\n\nWhen filming of ''Daisy of Love'' ended, Riggs was selected to be a part of another VH1 series ''[[I Love Money 3]]''. The show was never aired due to another contestant who killed his own wife before committing suicide.<ref name=\"Bio1\" />\n\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name=Jeremiah Riggs\n|names='''Jeremiah Riggs''',<br>Big Rigg,<br>Mississippi\n|image=\n|caption=\n|height={{height|feet=6|inch=0}}\n|weight={{convert|200|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1982|12|17}}\n|birth_place=[[Vicksburg, Mississippi]]\n|resides=[[Granite City, Illinois]],<br>[[Vicksburg, Mississippi]]\n|trainer= [[Matt Hughes (fighter)|Matt Hughes]],<br>[[Dutch Mantel]],<br>[[Bill DeMott]]\n}}\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\nRiggs began his professional wrestling career training with [[Dutch Mantel]] in [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Clendaniel |first=Brett |url=http://wrestlechat.net/dutch-mantel-endorses-a-wwe-tough-enough-candidate/ |title=Dutch Mantel Endorses a WWE Tough Enough Candidate |website=Wrestlechat.net |date=2015-12-18 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\n===WWE===\n\n====Tough Enough====\nIn March 2011, he was announced as one of the fourteen contestants for the return of ''[[WWE Tough Enough]]'' on the USA Network.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/22850/tuf-7-vet-jeremiah-riggs-set-for-wwes-tough-enough-series.mma |title=\"TUF 7\" vet Jeremiah Riggs set for WWE's \"Tough Enough\" series |author= |date=March 16, 2011 |website=MMAjunkie.com |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109160435/http://mmajunkie.com/news/22850/tuf-7-vet-jeremiah-riggs-set-for-wwes-tough-enough-series.mma |archivedate=November 9, 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref> Throughout the show, Riggs was complimented on his heart and athleticism. He was nicknamed \"MMA\" by the trainers because of his mixed martial arts background. Along with Martin, he was one of just two contestants to not get stuck in the bottom three. Riggs finished third on the show, being eliminated in week nine because of his inexperience inside the ring.\n\n====Florida Championship Wrestling (2011)====\nIn May 2011, Riggs made his debut for [[Florida Championship Wrestling]], the developmental territory for the WWE. He defeated [[Peter Orlov]] in his first match as a part of the ''Tough Enough'' finale.<ref name=\"FCWTE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/58150/detailed-spoilers-from-tough-enough-segments-taped-at-fcw-television-tapings.html?p=1|title=DETAILED SPOILERS FROM TOUGH ENOUGH SEGMENTS TAPED AT FCW TELEVISION TAPINGS|publisher=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> However, Riggs was released after being informed that WWE had no interest in signing him following the tryout in FCW after rubbing officials and other wrestlers the wrong way.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.aroundtheoctagon.com/jeremiah-riggs-blasts-fcw/ |title=Jeremiah Riggs blasts FCW |website=AroundTheOctagon.com |date=2011-08-02 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[The Ultimate Fighter]]'' || Himself || [[TV Series]]\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Daisy of Love]]'' || Himself || [[TV Series]]\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[WWE Tough Enough]]'' || Himself || [[TV Series]]\n|-\n| 2015 || [[Steve Austin's Broken Skull Challenge]] || Himself || [[TV Series]]\n|}\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n| draws= \n| nc= \n| ko-wins= 3\n| ko-losses= 1\n| sub-wins= 1\n| sub-losses= 5\n| dec-wins= 3\n| dec-losses= 2\n| dq-wins= \n| dq-losses= \n| other-wins= \n| other-losses= \n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 7\u20138\n| Peter Aspenwal\n| Decision (split)\n| [[Bellator 101]]\n| {{dts|2013|September|27}}\n| align=center| 3\n| align=center| 5:00\n| [[Portland, Oregon]], United States\n|\n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 7\u20137\n| [[Kelvin Tiller]]\n| Submission (Kimura)\n| [[Bellator Fighting Championships: Season Six#Bellator LXX|Bellator 70]]\n| {{dts|2012|May|25}}\n| align=center| 3\n| align=center| 3:38\n| [[New Orleans, Louisiana]], United States\n|\n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 7\u20136\n| Trey Houston\n| Submission (armbar)\n| [[Bellator 61#Bellator LXI|Bellator 61]]\n| {{dts|2012|March|16}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 3:30\n| [[Bossier City, Louisiana]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{Yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 7\u20135\n| Eric James Slocum\n| Decision (majority)\n| SportFight X: Middle Tennessee Mayhem\n| {{dts|2011|J